<font color="#FF0000">TO COOK BARELA</font><br>
<tt>Thu Oct 30 19:58:39 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Nah Cook,<br><br>
I ain't always right. We learn from our experiences. I have made many mistakes in my life.<br><br>
I never doubted that you know right from wrong. I think that as a policeman, upholding the law, you have to put your emotions and sympathies and predjudices aside and do what is RIGHT. People like me look up to law enforcement officers. I often talk to the young guys who are coming up, and try to show my appreciation. Might be the only time they ever hear it.<br><br>
When I returned from Vietnam, I began to hear people refer to policemen as being &quot;pigs&quot;. To me that was as bad as being called a baby killer. I hated the way that words were used in such disrespect towards men who laid their lives on the line every day. Showing respect is not political correctness.<br><br>
Cook, I don't believe that you see things only in black and white. True, you hold your ground quite well and stand up for what you believe in - very admirable. I think that your words have allowed many vets who read them to feel a sense of pride. I include myself among them.<br><br>
You &quot;let the cat out of the bag&quot; when you posted a couple of weeks ago that some of my posts made you rethink certain issues.<br><br>
Only the courageous admit as much. Others tend to muddle through their closemindedness - choosing to be stubborn and intractible. Black and white? Nah.<br><br>
I believe that this site has accomplished a great deal by allowing us to exchange viewpoints and ideas. It has not always been easy. But we have all learned through our lives, that good things don't usually come easy.<br><br>
Thanks for your service in Vietnam, for your performance of duty in the LAPD, and for your contributions here on this site.<br><br>
Best Regards,<br><br>
Tom
